IOT_QUESTIONS_PART10 = [{'question': 'An organisation is building an IoT security risk register. What unique risk categories must be included that are not typically found in an IT risk register?', 'options': [{'text': 'IoT risk registers are identical to IT risk registers requiring no additional categories', 'explanation': 'IoT introduces unique risk categories not typically present in IT risk registers including physical device risks, firmware supply chain risks, mass compromise risks, and end-of-support risks across large device fleets.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Physical device tampering mass device compromise supply chain firmware risks end-of-support device accumulation and IoT-specific regulatory compliance risks all require dedicated risk register categories', 'explanation': 'Correct. IoT-specific risk categories: physical device risks (tampering, theft, environmental damage), mass compromise risks (single vulnerability affecting entire fleet simultaneously), firmware supply chain risks (malicious updates affecting all devices), end-of-support accumulation (growing fleet of unpatched devices over time), IoT-specific regulatory risks (PSTI Act, EU Cyber Resilience Act, sector-specific IoT regulations), and cloud platform dependency risks (single platform failure affecting entire IoT operation).', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'IoT risks are fully captured by existing IT risk categories of confidentiality integrity and availability', 'explanation': 'While CIA applies to IoT the specific nature of IoT risks including physical consequences, mass fleet compromise patterns, and supply chain vectors require dedicated risk categories beyond the generic CIA framework.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'IoT risk registers should focus exclusively on data breach risks as this is the primary IoT security concern', 'explanation': 'Data breach is one IoT risk among many. Physical safety risks, operational disruption, mass device compromise, and supply chain risks are equally or more significant for many IoT deployments.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT risk register construction: identify all IoT device types and their risk profiles, assess each device type for physical, firmware, network, cloud, and supply chain risks, rate likelihood and impact considering mass compromise scenarios, identify compensating controls for high-rated risks, assign risk owners for each category, and review quarterly as the fleet evolves and new vulnerabilities emerge.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What is the Purdue Model adaptation for IoT environments and how does it extend the traditional OT security architecture?', 'options': [{'text': 'The Purdue Model does not apply to IoT environments as it was designed exclusively for OT systems', 'explanation': 'The Purdue Model principles of hierarchical network segmentation apply to IoT environments. IoT deployments connecting to OT systems particularly benefit from Purdue Model-inspired architecture separating IoT from OT and IT networks.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'IoT extends the Purdue Model by adding cloud connectivity layers above Level 4 requiring new security zones bridging IoT devices through edge gateways to cloud platforms while maintaining OT isolation', 'explanation': 'Correct. IoT extends Purdue by adding: Level 0-1 IoT sensors and actuators (similar to OT field devices), Level 2 IoT edge gateways (local processing and protocol translation), Level 3 IoT platform management (local device management), and cloud layers above Level 4 for IoT analytics and management. Security zones must prevent IoT cloud connectivity from creating paths into OT Levels 0-2.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'IoT deployments should be fully integrated with OT networks at all Purdue Model levels to enable maximum data sharing', 'explanation': 'Full integration of IoT with OT networks at all levels violates the security zone separation that the Purdue Model establishes. IoT cloud connectivity creates external-facing paths that must be carefully managed to prevent compromise paths into OT.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'The Purdue Model is obsolete for modern IoT deployments and should be replaced by a flat network architecture', 'explanation': 'The Purdue Model remains relevant for IoT in OT environments. Flat network architectures eliminate the security boundaries that limit lateral movement and blast radius of IoT compromises.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT in OT environments Purdue Model adaptation: IoT sensors at field level (Level 0-1) connect to IoT edge gateways (Level 2), edge gateways connect through DMZ to cloud platform (above Level 4), strict one-way data flow from OT to cloud via DMZ, no direct connectivity between IoT cloud platforms and OT control networks, and separate security zones for IoT management and OT management.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What is the security implication of consumer IoT devices being brought into enterprise environments by employees (BYOD IoT)?', 'options': [{'text': 'Consumer IoT devices brought to work have no security implications as they are on separate cellular or personal WiFi connections', 'explanation': 'Employees often connect personal IoT devices to enterprise WiFi creating network security risks. Even cellular-connected personal devices can create Bluetooth or WiFi attack vectors in enterprise spaces.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Personal IoT devices connecting to enterprise WiFi create unmanaged attack surfaces with unknown security posture potentially pivoting into corporate networks from poorly secured consumer devices', 'explanation': 'Correct. BYOD IoT risks: personal smart watches, fitness trackers, and smart speakers have unknown and typically weak security postures, connecting to enterprise WiFi puts them on corporate networks where compromise enables pivot attacks, enterprise IT has no visibility or control over personal IoT device security, personal devices may exfiltrate corporate conversations (smart speakers), and personal IoT device updates are at the user discretion not IT controlled.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'BYOD IoT is less risky than corporate IoT deployments because personal devices have stronger consumer security controls', 'explanation': 'Consumer IoT typically has weaker security than enterprise IoT. Consumer devices prioritise ease of use over security. BYOD IoT represents unmanaged devices with unknown security posture on corporate networks.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'BYOD IoT risks are eliminated by requiring employees to use a separate personal mobile data connection for all personal devices', 'explanation': 'While separate data connections for personal devices reduces some risks employees may still connect personal IoT to enterprise WiFi without separate data plans. Policy and technical controls both are required.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'BYOD IoT policy and technical controls: acceptable use policy defining which personal IoT devices are permitted on enterprise networks, separate guest VLAN for personal devices with internet-only access and no corporate network connectivity, Bluetooth usage policy for sensitive meeting environments, network access control blocking unknown devices from corporate VLAN, and employee awareness training on BYOD IoT risks.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What is the security challenge of IoT devices that use hard-coded cryptographic keys shared across all devices of the same model?', 'options': [{'text': 'Shared cryptographic keys are acceptable for IoT devices as they simplify key management at manufacturing scale', 'explanation': 'Shared cryptographic keys are a critical security vulnerability. Once a single device is compromised and the shared key extracted all devices using that key are simultaneously vulnerable.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Hard-coded shared keys mean extracting the key from one device compromises the entire fleet and the key cannot be rotated without a firmware update to all devices', 'explanation': 'Correct. Shared hard-coded key vulnerabilities: any attacker who extracts firmware from one device obtains the key protecting all devices, the key is effectively permanent as replacing it requires firmware updates to all deployed devices, the key may be available in firmware images distributed through public update channels, and the shared key enables impersonation of any device in the fleet.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Hard-coded keys are more secure than dynamically generated keys because they cannot be changed by attackers', 'explanation': 'The inability to change hard-coded keys is a vulnerability not a security feature. When a hard-coded key is compromised it cannot be rotated without firmware updates to every deployed device which may be impossible for large or legacy fleets.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Shared cryptographic keys only create risk if attackers can physically access the devices to extract the key', 'explanation': 'Keys can be extracted from firmware images without physical device access. Firmware obtained through update channels, leaked source code, or reverse engineering of device software can all expose hard-coded keys.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'Eliminating hard-coded shared keys: use unique per-device keys generated on-device or injected at manufacture using HSM, store keys in device secure elements preventing software extraction, implement key rotation capability through secure OTA process, use PKI-based device identity eliminating shared symmetric keys entirely, and audit existing IoT deployments for shared key usage as a critical vulnerability indicator.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'How should an organisation approach IoT security awareness training for employees who use or manage IoT devices?', 'options': [{'text': 'Standard IT security awareness training is sufficient for employees using IoT devices with no IoT-specific content needed', 'explanation': 'IoT security awareness requires specific content that standard IT training does not address including device onboarding procedures, recognition of compromised device indicators, USB and physical security for IoT devices, and BYOD IoT policies.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'IoT-specific training covering device onboarding procedures recognition of compromise indicators physical device security BYOD IoT policy and reporting procedures for suspected IoT security issues', 'explanation': 'Correct. IoT security awareness content: secure IoT device onboarding process (default credential change, network registration), recognising indicators of compromise (unexpected device behaviour, network anomalies), physical security of IoT devices (preventing tampering, reporting missing devices), BYOD IoT policy (what personal devices are permitted where), and clear reporting procedures for suspected IoT security issues including who to contact and what information to preserve.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Only IT administrators managing IoT infrastructure require IoT security training with no training needed for general employees', 'explanation': 'General employees who use IoT devices, observe unusual behaviour, or handle physical devices all benefit from IoT security awareness. Employees are often the first to notice IoT security anomalies and need to know how to report them.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'IoT security training should focus exclusively on phishing awareness as social engineering is the primary IoT attack vector', 'explanation': 'While social engineering targets employees interacting with IoT systems IoT security awareness covers a broader range including physical security, BYOD IoT, compromise recognition, and reporting procedures beyond phishing alone.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT security awareness programme: include IoT-specific module in annual security awareness training, provide role-based training for IoT device administrators covering technical security requirements, conduct tabletop exercises including IoT compromise scenarios, make reporting procedures clear and easy, and measure awareness through targeted IoT security phishing simulations and knowledge assessments.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What is the security consideration when IoT devices collect data about third parties who have not consented such as visitors to a smart building?', 'options': [{'text': 'Third party data collected by IoT devices is not subject to privacy regulations as only the building owner has a relationship with the data processor', 'explanation': 'Privacy regulations protect the rights of data subjects regardless of whether they have a direct relationship with the data processor. Visitors whose biometric or location data is collected by smart building IoT have privacy rights under GDPR and similar regulations.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Collecting data about non-consenting third parties creates regulatory obligations for transparency lawful basis signage and data minimisation even for visitors to smart buildings', 'explanation': 'Correct. Third-party data collection by IoT requires: lawful basis for processing visitor data (legitimate interest with balancing test or explicit consent), transparent notice (signage informing visitors of data collection), data minimisation collecting only what is necessary, retention limits for visitor data, mechanism for visitors to exercise data rights, and DPIA for high-risk processing like facial recognition or continuous location tracking of non-consenting individuals.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Prominent signage about IoT data collection fully satisfies all regulatory obligations for third-party data', 'explanation': 'Signage provides transparency but does not alone satisfy all regulatory obligations. Lawful basis, data minimisation, security measures, retention limits, and data subject rights mechanisms are all required in addition to transparency notices.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Third parties in public or semi-public spaces have no reasonable expectation of privacy making IoT data collection legally unrestricted', 'explanation': 'Privacy regulations protect individuals in public and semi-public spaces for certain categories of data collection especially biometric data and continuous location tracking. The reduced privacy expectation in public spaces is limited and does not eliminate all regulatory obligations.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'Third-party IoT data collection compliance: conduct DPIA before deploying IoT that collects visitor data, establish lawful basis (legitimate interest requires balancing test against visitor privacy interests), implement prominent transparent notice in all areas with IoT data collection, minimise data collected to only what is necessary for stated purpose, implement strict retention limits, and provide mechanism for individuals to enquire about their data.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What role does threat modelling play in IoT product security development and what frameworks are used?', 'options': [{'text': 'Threat modelling is only relevant during post-deployment security assessment and should not be done during IoT product development', 'explanation': 'Threat modelling is most valuable and cost-effective during the design and development phase when identified threats can be addressed through architecture decisions. Post-deployment remediation of design-level threats is significantly more expensive.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Threat modelling during IoT development identifies attack paths and informs security controls using frameworks like STRIDE and PASTA to systematically identify threats across all IoT architecture components', 'explanation': 'Correct. IoT threat modelling: STRIDE framework (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, Elevation of Privilege) applied to each IoT architecture component, PASTA (Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis) for risk-centric threat analysis, attack tree modelling for physical and cyber attack paths, data flow diagram analysis identifying trust boundaries, and threat model outputs informing security control selection and security testing scope.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Threat modelling for IoT is identical to threat modelling for web applications requiring no IoT-specific adaptations', 'explanation': 'IoT threat modelling must address unique attack surfaces including physical device access, firmware extraction, radio communication interception, and supply chain threats that web application threat modelling does not cover.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Threat modelling is too time-consuming for IoT development teams and should be replaced by penetration testing after deployment', 'explanation': 'Threat modelling identifies design-level issues that penetration testing often cannot detect and that are expensive to remediate after deployment. The time investment in threat modelling provides significant return through earlier and cheaper security issue identification.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT threat modelling process: create data flow diagrams for each IoT architecture component (device, gateway, cloud, mobile app), identify trust boundaries between components, apply STRIDE to each data flow and component, document threats and mitigations, prioritise by likelihood and impact, and use threat model to guide security testing scope. Update threat model when architecture changes.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What are the key differences between IoT security in developed markets with strong regulatory frameworks versus developing markets with limited IoT regulation?', 'options': [{'text': 'IoT security requirements are identical globally as all organisations should implement best practice regardless of regulatory environment', 'explanation': 'While best practice is universal the enforcement mechanisms, minimum requirements, and compliance obligations differ significantly between markets. These differences create practical implications for IoT security investment and risk management decisions.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Developing markets may have weaker baseline security requirements creating a two-tier global IoT security landscape where devices with lower security are sold in markets with less regulation creating import risks when those devices enter regulated markets', 'explanation': 'Correct. Regulatory disparity impacts: manufacturers may produce lower-security variants for less regulated markets reducing costs, these lower-security devices may be imported into regulated markets through grey market channels, global device fleets may have inconsistent security postures across regions, and attackers may preferentially target deployments in markets with weaker regulatory oversight and security requirements.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'IoT regulation has no impact on device security as manufacturers always implement maximum security regardless of regulatory requirements', 'explanation': 'Regulatory requirements directly influence manufacturer security investment decisions. Markets without minimum security requirements see lower-security products as manufacturers optimise for cost in the absence of regulatory minimum standards.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Developing market IoT devices are more secure than regulated market devices because they are built with simpler architecture', 'explanation': 'Simplicity of architecture does not correlate with security. Developing market IoT devices frequently have weaker security due to cost pressures and absence of regulatory minimum requirements.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'Global IoT security regulatory landscape: EU Cyber Resilience Act, UK PSTI Act, and US IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act establish minimum requirements in major markets. Procurement controls should specify security requirements beyond regional minimums. Grey market import controls should verify devices meet destination market security requirements. Global device fleet management should enforce consistent security standards regardless of regional regulatory minimums.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'What is the significance of the IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act passed in the United States and what requirements does it establish?', 'options': [{'text': 'The IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act applies to all IoT devices sold in the United States including consumer products', 'explanation': 'The IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act specifically applies to IoT devices purchased by the US federal government not to all consumer products. Consumer IoT regulation in the US is addressed through separate regulatory efforts.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'The IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act requires IoT devices purchased by the US federal government to meet NIST security guidelines establishing minimum security baselines for government IoT procurement', 'explanation': 'Correct. The IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act of 2020 directs NIST to develop and publish security standards and guidelines for IoT devices owned or controlled by federal agencies. It requires federal agencies to only purchase IoT devices that meet these NIST standards effectively establishing a government procurement baseline that influences broader market standards.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'The IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act mandates IoT security certifications for all manufacturers selling products in the United States', 'explanation': 'The Act focuses on federal government procurement requirements not mandatory certification for all US market participants. Voluntary frameworks and separate regulatory efforts address broader US market IoT security.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'The IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act has no practical impact as NIST guidelines are voluntary and unenforceable', 'explanation': 'NIST guidelines under this Act are mandatory for federal government IoT procurement. While not broadly mandatory their adoption in government procurement influences market-wide IoT security practices and creates de facto standards.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act impact: NIST SP 800-213 developed under this Act provides comprehensive IoT security guidance, federal government procurement requirements create market incentives for compliance beyond the government sector, the Act enables NIST to define minimum security baselines for government IoT that inform broader best practice, and it complements sector-specific IoT requirements across critical infrastructure sectors.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}, {'question': 'Looking across all IoT security domains what approach best summarises an effective IoT security strategy for most organisations?', 'options': [{'text': 'Purchase the most comprehensive IoT security platform available and rely on it to address all IoT security requirements', 'explanation': 'No single platform addresses all IoT security requirements. Effective IoT security requires a programme approach covering governance, procurement, device security, network security, monitoring, and incident response across the device lifecycle.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Implement a lifecycle approach covering secure procurement visibility through asset inventory network segmentation device authentication monitoring and incident response with continuous improvement as the fleet and threat landscape evolve', 'explanation': 'Correct. Effective IoT security strategy: secure procurement (vendor assessment, security requirements in contracts), visibility (complete asset inventory of all IoT devices), network protection (segmentation, access controls), device security (unique credentials, firmware management), monitoring (anomaly detection, incident alerting), incident response (IoT-specific procedures), governance (policies, risk management, compliance), and continuous improvement responding to new threats, vulnerabilities, and regulations.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Focus exclusively on network security as IoT device-level security is the vendor responsibility not the deploying organisation', 'explanation': 'Effective IoT security requires both network and device-level controls. Network controls limit blast radius but do not address device-level vulnerabilities. Both dimensions are organisation responsibilities in the shared responsibility model.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Implement IoT security controls only for high-value IoT devices and accept the risk of unmanaged low-value devices', 'explanation': 'Low-value IoT devices can be compromised and used for high-impact attacks including DDoS, lateral movement, and data collection. Risk-based prioritisation is appropriate but unmanaged devices should not simply be accepted as low risk without assessment.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT security programme maturity model: Initial (ad hoc, reactive) → Developing (basic controls, inconsistent) → Defined (documented programme, consistently applied) → Managed (measured and monitored) → Optimising (continuous improvement). Most organisations should target Defined maturity covering the full lifecycle from procurement through decommissioning with documented policies, consistent technical controls, and measured outcomes.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Governance and Risk'}]